					<item>
		<title><![CDATA[Adapting This Method]]></title>
		<link>https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?post_type=back-matter&#038;p=23</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 07 Jun 2024 18:32:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[misbell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?post_type=back-matter&#038;p=23</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[A book becomes a textbook when it's authored by someone who isn't your teacher. It's a very different dynamic when the teacher is the one giving the guidance. This is why we've openly licensed this resource. We want instructors to have the freedom to customize the introduction. Maybe your metaphor for reading isn't The Station as we've envisioned it, but something else. Maybe the units and assignments focus on aspects of literature other than the narrative elements we've used to structure assignments. We'd love to hear what you've done with this text--please let us know and we'll include a link to your adaptation at the bottom of this page!

This course focuses on the long nineteenth century, but it could be adapted to any historical survey by showing students how to find texts they’ve never read that fall in the period being studied (perhaps even encouraging them to explore texts beyond those most commonly assigned). For a course focusing on a specific genre or literary movement, this same approach can work. The trick to eliminating the reading list is figuring out how to help students find new-to-them texts in the period, genre, or movement being studied. These classifications are interpretive (does it matter most when a text was originally published or when it experienced a resurgence in popularity?); we expect that fuzzy boundaries can be very productive to this method.

Assignments in this course asked students to compose posts for a website that was only visible to members of the class during the semester. Students were able to choose whether they wanted to share discussion reflections and formal assignments with the instructor or the entire class. As seen in the final project options below, the course website also allowed students to prepare their writing to be fully public at the end of the semester. This option for students to share their writing with classmates is an important feature of the course. The website also makes it possible for the instructor to read what students are thinking at the end of class discussions (and emphasize the importance of participation by giving credit for reflections as complete or incomplete). Discussion reflections reveal where students are getting stuck (things they might not volunteer during discussion).

In this course, we encourage students to think of literary techiques/forms/inventions as tools that help humans respond to environmental problems. We think that literary scholarship has only started to identify these tools in the available literature and that students can participate in this process, perhaps alerting us to techniques we haven’t yet encountered. Our primary goal is to help students prepare to explore new works of literature for the rest of their lives.

Literature courses differ based on the techniques of explanation, discussion, and independent work that an instructor uses. This course departs from many longstanding techniques within these three realms to try something new.

1. Instead of facilitating interpretation-based discussion of a shared text, instructors help students learn how to articulate their experiences reading texts they have chosen. This puts students in the position of ownership of their reading. The instructor has an opportunity to volunteer interesting context or interpretive possibilities the student might not be aware of when offering feedback on assignments.
2. Instead of instructors contextualizing assigned reading with historical context or the explanation of formal features, students are given the responsibility of finding these things on their own. Instructor expertise is much more important in this process because they are drawing on their knowledge of literary history on the fly or modeling their own research process when they’re not sure of the answer (which will be a common occurrence!). This change can happen primarily because we now live in an era of knowledge abundance. The context for understanding texts is not only available to the professor to be disseminated to students through a lecture.
3. Instead of producing papers of literary analysis, students chronicle their reading experiences and their process of identifying features and literary techniques that prompted their reactions. We have set aside “English paper” assignments because we see literature instruction as distinct from writing instruction. The teaching of logic and other tools of academic argumentation is valuable and happens in writing courses. To assess student learning in the realm of literature, we are not testing them on how well they can recall specific texts, contexts, ad themes. Instead, we ask them to make sense of a text they’ve never encountered before and assess how efficiently they’re taking advantage of resources to make sense of the unfamiliar.]]></content:encoded>
