					<item>
		<title><![CDATA[Getting Started]]></title>
		<link>https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?post_type=chapter&#038;p=5</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 07 Jun 2024 15:27:46 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[misbell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?p=5</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[This course focuses on the literature of the long nineteenth century. So, for the majority of the semester, you’ll be choosing texts that were published between the years 1789 and 1914. But we’re not doing that quite yet. As we get started, you’re going to select a story you've already experienced--one that prompted a memorable experience. We know that this can seem a bit daunting. Maybe you’re not in the habit of reading these days or maybe you don’t think the stories you consume are worth mentioning in a “literature” class. Trust us, this process will work with any story (a novel, film, album, videogame, etc). This is because all stories (from Star Wars to Beowulf and from Hamlet to Bridgerton) are fundamentally tools that do work on our brains. These tools are crafted by artisans (authors, content creators, stand-up comics, songwriters, video game developers) who draw on an ever-expanding set of techniques as they create. Literature scholars like to argue about which stories are superior (this is why we have a literary canon), but if it has a character doing something, it’s a story.

In other words, be honest about what you like! Your semester will be most enjoyable if you use this first assignment to explore what you genuinely enjoy. We hope to show you that there are many other stories that have provoked similar experiences in others. If it’s hard to pick just one story, you can go through this process for two or three different stories. The more you explore in this assignment, the more you’ll discover about your preferences.

Once you’ve decided on the story (or stories) that you’ll explore in this assignment, make sure you have access to it. It’s often been the case that students don’t have a copy of the book they read five years ago or don’t have the right console to play a specific video game on campus. Talk to your professor and your library if this is the case. Within the two weeks you’ll spend on this assignment, there should be time to track it down. You can also change your choice if it turns out you can’t access the story. You will need to be able to quote from it to meet the requirements of this assignment.

Our goal is to isolate specific story experiences and then try to figure out which specific features of the story prompted those experiences. Once we’ve isolated the features of the story, we’ll try to figure out the technique the author used to create those features. We’ll do this step by step and you’ll submit a piece of writing that shows your thought process. This means that you are not (for this or any assignment this semester) going to be asked to produce a traditional “English paper” (clear thesis statement supported with evidence from the text). Instead, you are going to describe, explore, and chronicle your process figuring out how you think the story works. You might feel an urge to find out if others have already figured it out and it’s fine to do this (though definitely not required). If you find a resource that offers an explanation, make sure to cite it! You may not figure everything out, and that’s okay.
<h1>Describe your Experience</h1>
Describe how you came to experience the story you’ve chosen and what you remember about the experience. Try to remember the year or even the specific time of year (this will be helpful after you’ve turned the assignment in). Most importantly, try to put into words the emotions you experienced.
<h1>Classify your Experience</h1>
Now that you've described your experience, think about whether that experience is something others have felt. This might be a little challenging because it's not how we typically talk about literature. People interpret literature in all sorts of different ways--that was something I loved the most about it when I was a college student. But you're not thinking about whether someone reached a similar interpretation as you. You're trying to decide if others have had a similar experience. You can see in the list of experiences below that it's quite separate from your interpretation. What we're doing here is using a scientific method similar to what naturalists use when they work from observation in the field to taxonomic classification. If they encounter something that hasn't already been classified, they give it a name and call it a new species (after conferring with other scientists, of course). In the list of experiences below, you might find one that captures the experience you had. If your experience isn't there, you get to name it and, if you want, add it into our list of experiences.
<ul>
 	<li>I felt a sense of wonder (15)</li>
 	<li>I got lost in the story and forgot about my own problems (p. 17)</li>
 	<li>I felt less alone in my trauma</li>
 	<li>I felt courageous (like I would do something even if I was afraid) (34-35)</li>
 	<li>I felt like I was part of a larger community</li>
 	<li>I felt love or emotional connection</li>
 	<li>I felt forgiveness</li>
</ul>
<h1>Describe the features prompting your experience</h1>
Here’s where it becomes important to have access to the story as you do this assignment. Return to the story and try to determine what exactly it was about the story that shaped your experience. Was it some aspect of the plot? Was it the way the narrator told the story? Was it a surprising character? Was it some aspect of the world the author created? It might be a combination of features so include everything! If it’s specific language from the story, include direct quotation in this section. If it is something that can’t be quoted (some aspect of the plot or some feel of the storyworld), put it into your own words with as much detail as possible.

Example of direction quotation:

Example of paraphrase:
<h1>Theorize about/Try to determine the technique that created the feature</h1>
Now that you have figured out which features of the story prompted your experience, try to imagine the technique the author used to create that feature. We say imagine because that’s exactly how this sort of analysis works. You probably can’t know exactly what the author(s) did or why they did it (even if they explain it in an interview!) so the trick is to wrap your head around the fact that this thing you experienced was created deliberately by someone (or, more likely, a team of people). These people created the storyworld, made choices about the plot, decided to narrate the story in a particular way (this involves specific camera angles if you’re looking at film or video games), and crafted characters. There might have been discussions (even arguments) between authors and editors, screenwriters and directors, or game designers and graphics editors. What set of decisions do you think prompted your emotional response and who is most likely responsible for it? [Mike should check out the director of photography on that film]

<strong><em>Each Story-Experience-Feature-Technique linkage is one unit. This assignment requires you to identify at least one unit, but you can repeat this process for however many distinct experiences you had with a story. You can also repeat this process for however many stories you want to explore.</em></strong>

[pull in full list here or link to the list in the glossary?]

The stretch: taking a regular pattern of plot or character or storyworld or narrative style and extending the pattern further.

<strong>Plot</strong>
plot twist
hurt delay (storyteller constructs a way for trauma to strike a character without the character realizing it…audience knows the trauma before it is felt by the character) (18-22)

<strong>Narrator</strong>
metaphor
human God voice (a narrator who did what a sung paean did: give our brain the feeling of joining a holy chorus that sensed danger nearby) (37)
the Almighty Heart (39)
Intimate disclosure + Wonder (54) [any lyric voice that lays baare a private feeling…any he-she-they story that make makes a personal disclosure about its characters]

<strong>Storyworld</strong>

<strong>Character</strong>
heroic character
<h1>Discuss your choices</h1>
Before submitting your final draft, we will take time in class to discuss what you've discovered. In class, I'll ask you to share the following information from your draft post in our shared Word Online document. We'll focus especially on any new experiences and techniques you might have discovered in your process.
<ul>
 	<li>Literary Work you're writing about</li>
 	<li>Experiences you had while reading (up to three)</li>
 	<li>For each experience, which of the following elements of narrative do you think caused the experience?</li>
 	<li>What technique do you think the creator used to prompt that experience?</li>
</ul>]]></content:encoded>
