					<item>
		<title><![CDATA[Introduction]]></title>
		<link>https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?post_type=front-matter&#038;p=4</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 07 Jun 2024 15:27:46 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[misbell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?p=4</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>

Welcome to The Station. I’m guessing by the way you’re gazing around that you haven’t been here before?

It’s incredible, right? It’s something about the combination of natural light that’s coming in, and the stone arches, and the marble floor, and the murals on every surface that isn’t a window (200,000 windows, to be precise). Yes, they are shaped like diamonds though I can't tell you the exact reason why.

I’ve always struggled to put into words exactly how it feels to be in this space. It’s all of the things I love about train stations and airports: loads of people hustling here and there, the acoustics (everything slightly dampened so it’s like this hushed loudness...very calming...like Grand Central Station).

But then also it’s none of the things that make those places terrible. No running down a sweltering platform to catch the final train of the night. No loud screetching of brakes and wheels on rails, no airport security to go through, no “paging John Smith, your plane is boarding." There's a massive arrival and departure board, but no one's staring at it anxiously.

Can you believe that there was a time when people had to travel by horse, or travel for months on the ocean to reach their destinations? That departure and arrival board—the idea that there could be a regular schedule so that anyone could buy a ticket to join other travelers to get pretty much anywhere on Earth…what a stunning feat of human engineering! But, our departure and arrival board is more like a museum piece. Kind of like, see over there? In that corner is an Airstream trailer. You can go inside and sit down and have a snack (endless s'mores). And over there is a stagecoach. You can climb up and crack the whip (they don’t keep the horses here anymore…people kept feeding them).

Anyway, what was I saying? Oh, right. The departure and arrival board doesn’t mean anything (they keep it running because it looks cool). We don’t use it because at The Station you can leave for a destination the second you decide where you want to go. If you look right behind you, it looks like someone is departing right now. Oh yes, that's Toby. He's here all the time.

Come closer so you can see…he's decided where he's going so he's walking up to a free window.

Did you hear what he said? He whispered it so you might not have caught it. He said “Howard’s End.” See how there’s this faint etching of words appearing on the glass? That’s going to fade in just a moment as he…ah, he did it. He went to touch the etched glass and his hand went through it. He just climbed right through the window. No, I don't think he's scared…he’s done this before.

Yeah, that's right. He's gone now. Not just like, outside the window but on a journey to Howard's End.

Now the glass is glass again. You can tap it if you want. Yeah, I honestly don't know how it works. Some people have been studying it...they've published articles on the physics of this particular place and why it's different than other transportation hubs.

Oh, and look over there! A whole family is going together! The dad is whispering to the window and…they’re all just diving in head first! Yeah, you can definitely go on a journey with other people. It happens all the time.

Oh, don’t worry. Toby can come back whenever he wants. Look over here, someone’s just arriving from a journey. See those massive tubes of frosted glass in the center there? They're all bending toward the center of The Station.

Yes, good point! They ARE a little bit like those tubes at the bank! It's kind of like everyone's in their own little cylinder. I guess they never quite found a mechanism quite so elegant as that.

It’s pretty fun to see people flying back from their journeys. The designers really focused on making the experience of returning pleasant. You just feel like you’re floating as you enter the station—all of your limbs are supported in exactly the right way. It feels like a million little puffs of the perfect temperature of air. I think it smells a little bit like popcorn and Parmesan cheese when I come back. Like puppy paws, you know? Maybe that’s just me though, others have said it smells like sunbum sunscreen. Maybe it’s whatever smell you love the most?

Here, let's ask someone.

Excuse me. Um, hi. I see you’ve just returned from a journey. Can I ask you sort of a weird question? What did it feel like as you returned to The Station?

“Like I was being hugged, but not too tight. And…it smelled like the leaves of a tomato plant. Sorry, uh…I have to go submit my experience”

"Oh yes, of course. Don't let me keep you."

Yeah, I'll definitely explain what's happening now. It'll be very new to you, I think. He's going over to that red glowing sphere in the center of the room. It's called RED. To me, it has darkroom vibes. You seem pretty young. Did you know that before digital cameras and smartphones people had to develop their film before they could see their pictures? The photographic materials are very sensitive to light, so in order to see what they were doing, photographers would use red light in the room.

Oh, sorry to have assumed you wouldn't know. You totally get it then. Darkroom vibes. Everyone's illuminated by RED's glow over there. Pretty magical.

Yeah, so he just plopped down in one of the comfy chairs around RED...he's looking at his notebook, scribbling a bit. It seems like he took notes on his journey. Some people just rely on what they remember, but most people (myself included, to be honest) take notes on their journeys. If you want to submit something to RED, you just find a spot to sit and take a little time to process your journey. There are people he can talk to about his experiences...he’s also going to try to figure out what exactly prompted those experiences. There's nothing really extra special about the people he's talking to, no...they're just fellow travelers. Once he’s processed a bit, he’s going to put his hand on RED to submit his experience. That part is super cool. Let's wait a bit and see if we can see someone doing that.

[drums fingers...waits awkwardly]

I mean, you could go talk to him and help him think about his journey. Do you want me to introduce you? You could just say, like... "hey, Brah. What was it like where you went?"

No?

Well, you can just say whatever. Or, you don't have to. You do you.

[...]

Oh, good. whew. Someone's going up to RED. You see how when she puts her hand on the surface of the glass it glows? If we were close enough (but we really shouldn't crowd her) we'd be able to see that it's bringing up different options for her to select. It's like navigating a smart phone...it even has that sort of haptic thing where you feel a satisfying clunk as you drop the experience you've chosen into the right spot. And then it says really nice things to you when you take the time to try to identify what it was about the trip that caused your experience. Yeah, like "what a clever observation" and "wow, you just made someone's day sharing that!"

Just don't put something in the wrong place or it'll electrocute you!

HAHA...just kidding. That won't happen. There is no wrong answer with RED. I mean the tool will sort of organize what you submit to make it as useful as possible to other travelers, but whatever you put in there stays just as you put it. You can go back and look at all of the experiences you've logged over time, which is actually super fun.

No, he doesn’t HAVE to enter his experiences there. No requirement to submit experiences to RED. Most people (myself included) do it because they want others to know how great their journeys were. Everyone is different of course so people can have very different experiences visiting the same place, but sometimes people come to the station and don’t really have any ideas about where they want to go. They just go up to RED, peruse the places other travelers have gone, and decide what they want to try.

Oh, there is one thing that RED doesn't like...I actually accidentally did it when I first started coming here. I'd gone on a journey and completely could not process what happened while I was there. They spoke a different language there, and there were all sorts of jarring sensations. It was pretty uncomfortable and when I came back I was like "I can't put that into RED! I don't want to muddy up the experiences with this hot mess." So I asked around to other people who had been there before. I found this guy who had the most brilliant things to say about the language. I didn't realize it wasn't allowed at that point...I just selected things that sounded like what he told me and found a random detail in my notes to throw in to make it seem real. Even before I finished my submission a fellow traveler came up and said "wow, that doesn't seem like the sort of thing you've said before...tell me more about that experience" and I said "Oh, uh...I didn't know what to say so I asked other people." She said to me in the kindest way...like, I really wasn't afraid..."come with me." She took me over to this quiet spot in the back of The Station. There was music playing---like the minecraft soundtrack or maybe it was that music they put on in spas? And she asked me to sit down on this really comfy couch. She sat across from me and she said "tell me what it was like." And I told her. I told her all of the messy details. She smiled and nodded and--I couldn't believe it--"THAT," she said, "is what you need to put into RED. That is a brilliant observation! She was amazing.

</div>
Okay, I can tell you're ready to go. Lots of people navigate The Station completely on their own and you can totally do that too as soon as you’re ready. I’ve been traveling through The Station for YEARS (some might say millenia). I love explaining how it works, but I'm learning how to be quiet and let people do what they will. I'll be here if you have a question. I love questions!

Okay.

Good luck! And have fun.]]></content:encoded>
