					<item>
		<title><![CDATA[Reading Experiences]]></title>
		<link>https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?post_type=chapter&#038;p=150</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 13 Jun 2024 18:36:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[misbell]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://unewhaven.pressbooks.pub/searchingforwonder/?post_type=chapter&#038;p=150</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[This glossary is an ever-expanding collection of experiences from readers of literature, arranged alphabetically. Beneath each experience is a brief definition (including any other terms we treat as synonyms), a neuroscientific explanation of the experience, and benefits that have emerged from the experience.
<h1>Connection</h1>
&nbsp;
<h1><strong>Courage</strong></h1>
<strong>The feeling of being genuinely afraid of something and simultaneously bold enough to face it. Also referred to as "bravery."
</strong>

<strong>Neurochemical Experience</strong>: Courage begins in the amygdala, which senses danger and panics, triggering our “sympathetic nervous system, our periaqueductal gray matter, and the other components of our brain’s threat-response network to release a mix of adrenaline and natural opioid painkillers, boosting our heart rate, numbing our hurt, and filling us with energy” (35). This biological response is meant to help us flee dangerous situations, but it “can be converted into bravery through the addition of one more neural ingrediant: oxytocin.” Oxytocin bonds mothers to newborns. The release is made by our pituitary gland, “a more courageous part of our inner brain that sits just below our amygdala in a bone command bunker, the sella turcica. When the pituitary recognizes that there are “other endangered humans in our vicinity, it releases oxytocin.

<strong>Benefit</strong>: Referred to as "tend and befriend" in the scientific literature, the experience of courage prompts human beings to help others in a crisis. “In times of chronic danger, such as famine or plague, tend and befriend encourages us to share our food and our medicines with the other threatened people sensed by our pituitary. And in times of acute danger (like an ambush), it prompts us to band together in a combat pack. Within that pack, we’re more likely to endure than as a fleeing person. We can stave off—even conquer—threats that would devour us alone" (35)
<h1>Forgiveness</h1>
<h1>Love</h1>
While reading, you...
<h1>Trauma Reduction</h1>
<h1>Wonder</h1>]]></content:encoded>
